{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619463"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16554"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16554"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.31,0.15,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75763"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9245"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61277"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7193"},{"type":"tags","id":"10359"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21907"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75763"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe relationship between cranial nerves and adjacent blood vessels is clinically significant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves emerges between the superior cerebellar artery and the posterior cerebral artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olfactory nerve (cranial nerve I)","Optic nerve (cranial nerve II)","Oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III)","Trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV)","Trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III)\u003C/strong\u003E emerges from the interpeduncular fossa of the midbrain between the superior cerebellar artery and posterior cerebral artery. This anatomical relationship is important as compression or aneurysm of these vessels can affect nerve function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other cranial nerves have different anatomical relationships:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory nerve (cranial nerve I)\u003C/strong\u003E emerges from the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic nerve (cranial nerve II)\u003C/strong\u003E emerges from the optic disc and passes through the optic canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV)\u003C/strong\u003E emerges from the dorsal surface of the brainstem\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V)\u003C/strong\u003E emerges from the pons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these neurovascular relationships is crucial for interpreting symptoms of compression syndromes and planning neurosurgical approaches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III) emerges from the midbrain between the superior cerebellar artery and posterior cerebral artery.","The relationship between cranial nerves and adjacent blood vessels is important for understanding neurovascular compression syndromes."],"references":["Joyce C, Le PH, Peterson DC. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 3 (Oculomotor). 2023 Mar 27. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725811.","B\u0142aszczyk M, Ochwat K, Necka S, Kwieci\u0144ska M, Ostrowski P, Bonczar M, \u017bytkowski A, Walocha J, Mitu\u015b J, Koziej M. The Arterial Anatomy of the Cerebellum-A Comprehensive Review. Brain Sci. 2024 Jul 29;14(8):763. doi: 10.3390/brainsci14080763. PMID: 39199457; PMCID: PMC11352334.","Netter, F. H. (2015).\u00a0Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16554"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61277"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T14:35:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T07:55:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9245"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75763"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"e